    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3221877560" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3221877560" />
    <a title="Marija" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/85343914-marija"><img alt="Marija" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1624962551p2/85343914.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3221877560?book_show_action=true">Mar 09, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Marija" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Marija" href="/user/show/85343914-marija">Marija</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/85343914-marija?shelf=adventure">adventure</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/85343914-marija?shelf=fantasy">fantasy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/85343914-marija?shelf=young-adult">young-adult</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/85343914-marija?shelf=fairy-tale">fairy-tale</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/85343914-marija?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3221877560" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12793673554199725672">*contains spoilers <br/><br/>After <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/7948410.Secondhand_Charm' title='Secondhand Charm by Julie Berry' rel='nofollow noopener'>Secondhand Charm</a> by the author without much thought I jumped to <i>Amaranth Enchantment</i>, also the book I removed and added from my TBR list so many times. The rating seemed kind of low and the reviews said -too childish- so no need to say; I had zero expectations... And here we are!<br/><br/><i>The setting</i> Again like <i>Secondhand Charm</i> in some fiction-land Kingdom, medieval times(?), I can even less specify in here. <br/><br/><i>The Plot</i> We have <b>an orphan, 15 yo Lucinda</b> slaving in her <b>Aunt and Uncle&apos;s</b></span>
  <span id="freeText12793673554199725672" style="display:none">*contains spoilers <br><br>After <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/7948410.Secondhand_Charm" title="Secondhand Charm by Julie Berry" rel="nofollow noopener">Secondhand Charm</a> by the author without much thought I jumped to <i>Amaranth Enchantment</i>, also the book I removed and added from my TBR list so many times. The rating seemed kind of low and the reviews said -too childish- so no need to say; I had zero expectations... And here we are!<br><br><i>The setting</i> Again like <i>Secondhand Charm</i> in some fiction-land Kingdom, medieval times(?), I can even less specify in here. <br><br><i>The Plot</i> We have <b>an orphan, 15 yo Lucinda</b> slaving in her <b>Aunt and Uncle's Goldsmithy</b>. She is constantly cleaning and being punished by her Aunt no matter what she does. <br>So expecting something of a Cinderella story.<br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1596718344i/29924669.jpg" height="250" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>She was having a 'normal' day when the lonely and unpopular Goldsmihty visit two very important people (not at the same time) and things from here go downhill.<br><br><i>Characters</i> <br><b>Lucinda</b> was, in my opinion, <b>better fleshed out</b> than Evie in <i>Secondhand Charm</i>, where Evie's action left me with a question mark, Lucinda <b>felt steady and true to herself</b>. But still, I didn't get at all why Lucinda had insta-love with the love interest. I found the whole relationship wanting and not developed i.e. it should have progressed more slowly to give time to the readers to understand the relationship. Cause I don't. <br><br><b>Peter, the thief</b>, oh my Brain cells, on one hand, he is one person who got so much on my nerves. On the other hand, he is very well developed; he is a thief, <b>a charmer with great ambitions and skills, but also displayed some gentle sides at moments</b>. But! oh gee! whenever Lucinda had a conversation with him my brain was exploding!!<br><br><b>George, the prince</b>, well he is a <b>people's person</b>, he is good-looking, confident, girls are dying to be by his side. Yes, he is a charmer but he is also a goody, considerate and open. and later to my shock, he is so good! He displayed such a considerate and utterly lovable characteristic I was captivated...<br><br><b>Amaranth Witch, with Lucinda's aunt, and the bad guy</b>. Here we have the so-so parallels with <b>Christian mythology</b>. The Witch and the bad guy as the<b> fallen angels. </b><br><br>They weren't satisfied with their lives in their heaven, something internally 'dragged' them down and they left their heaven and when they came to Earth they couldn't deal with human feelings, they come to get and did horrible things.<br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1596718344i/29924670._SY540_.jpg" height="250" alt="description" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br><b>CHRISTIAN ASPECT OF THE STORY</b> big spoilers ahead:<br>The main trio was sure multi-layered but in my opinion, the Witch was the best! <b>She </b>(and Lucinda's aunt but her deed is little in shadow compared to the Witch's deed) <b>was the one who transcended the things she has done.</b> Parallel to the bad guy who didn't. This where Christianity stands, she didn't continue to do bad stuff once she has done it and "oh I did this I'm a bad person so be it I can't change who I'm..." like the bad guy who plunged and just went deeper in sin or whatever you want to call it. <br><br>For years and years, she lived with the guilt and the burden that drains the energy till she raised herself from that framework and <b>as a real angel helped Lucinda</b> and did the one thing she had to.<b> Seek forgiveness.</b> Granted sometimes it is harder to forgive others, the things that people said or did to you it feels like the deed done to you is soo great you just can't-that it's unimaginably heavy. But imagine the situation being the person who did something wrong and going to the victim, the person who holds your deeds in your hand so to say and completely free to judge you and dismiss you like the tramp you believe yourself to be. I think no one would want to be in a situation where he has to admit he did wrong at all and to humble himself. The definition of horror<br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1596718344i/29924671._SX540_.jpg" height="250" alt="description" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>Conclusion: The story has so <b>many symbols</b> I like so much but the <b>ending felt rushed</b> it left me unsatisfied. The reread is on my priority list and no matter it's ending I warmly recommend <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/3843654.The_Amaranth_Enchantment" title="The Amaranth Enchantment by Julie Berry" rel="nofollow noopener">The Amaranth Enchantment</a> To judge, to hate, to love, or whatever, but to give it a go :)</span>
  <a data-text-id="12793673554199725672" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

